recedents, have influenced every justice since 1950. The authors find considerable variation in how these doctrines affect each justice, variation due in part to the differing experiences justices have brought to the bench. Second, Bailey and Maltzman show that justices are constrained by political factors. Justices are not isolated from what happens in the legislative and executive branches, and instead respond in predictable ways to changes in the preferences of Congress and the president. The Constrained Court shatters the myth that justices are unconstrained actors who pursue their personal policy preferences at all costs. By showing how law and politics interact in the construction of American law, this book sheds new light on the unique role that the Supreme Court plays in the constitutional order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 7aLAW / Court Rules.2bisacsh  aAmerican law.  aCourt behavior.  aCourt voting.  aRichard Nixon.  aSupreme Court justices.  aU.S. Congress.  aU.S. president.  aattitudinal model.  aconstitution.  aconstitutional cases.  aconstitutional order.  adecision making.  adeference.  aelected branches.  aexecutive branch.  aexecutive influence.  ahistorical context.  ajudicial decision-making.  ajudicial decisions.  ajudicial preferences.  ajudicial restraint.  ajudiciary.  alaw.  alegal constraints.  alegal doctrine.  alegal doctrines.  alegal values.  apersonal experiences.  apersonal policy preference.  apolicy preference.  apolicy preferences.  apolitical system.  apolitics.  aprecedent.  aprecedents.  apresident.  asolicitor general.  astare decisis.  astatutory cases.1 aMaltzman, Forrest, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle i